    exp:'Rising LRAC as output grows is the definition of <strong>diseconomies of scale</strong> &mdash; the firm has moved onto the upward-sloping right-hand section of the LRAC curve. Likely causes: communication breakdown across a very large organisation, difficulty co-ordinating complex logistics, management losing touch with frontline operations, or X-inefficiency as competitive discipline weakens with scale.<br><br>B is wrong: at MES, LRAC is at its <em>minimum</em>, not rising. C is wrong: movements along a <em>SRAC</em> curve don\'t change LRAC by definition. D is possible as a separate event, but the question says the firm "doubled its output" and LRAC rose &mdash; the most parsimonious explanation is diseconomies, not a cost-curve shift.'
