        answer:'Normal profit is the minimum return an entrepreneur needs to keep their resources in their current use rather than switching to the next best alternative. It is therefore an opportunity cost and is included in a firm\'s economic costs. This means when a firm earns normal profit, its economic profit is exactly zero &mdash; total revenue covers all costs including the required return to the entrepreneur. Only returns above normal profit are classified as supernormal profit.'
