    ans:0,
    exp:'The odd one out is <strong>leasing assets on short-term contracts</strong>. By converting capital expenditure into a variable, recoverable cost, leasing dramatically reduces sunk costs and therefore lowers the exit penalty. This makes "hit and run" entry much more credible: a firm can enter a market, compete, and exit without losing its investment. The other three all <em>reduce</em> contestability by raising sunk costs (brand investment), locking up inputs (exclusive contracts), or creating irrecoverable capital (purpose-built infrastructure).'
