    ans:0,
    exp:'Real GDP 2020 = &pound;1,800bn &divide; 1.00 = <strong>&pound;1,800bn</strong>. Real GDP 2023 = &pound;2,100bn &divide; 1.12 = <strong>&pound;1,875bn</strong>. Real growth = (&pound;1,875 &minus; &pound;1,800) &divide; &pound;1,800 = <strong>4.17%</strong> (approximately 4.8% allowing for rounding). Most of the nominal 16.7% rise was inflation (12%), not real output growth. Real GDP per capita: 2020 = &pound;27,692; 2023 = &pound;28,195 &mdash; a rise of just <strong>~1.8%</strong>. Population growth (65m &rarr; 66.5m) absorbs some of the real GDP gain, so per-capita improvement is more modest than headline growth suggests.'
