  { type:'confidence_mcq',
    stem:'The concept of <strong>hysteresis</strong> in macroeconomics suggests that:',
    opts:[
      'A prolonged recession can permanently reduce the economy&apos;s productive capacity (LRAS shifts left) because workers lose skills, capital depreciates, and investment is foregone',
      'The economy always returns to its previous level of output after a recession ends, regardless of how long the downturn lasted',
      'Supply-side policies have no long-term effect on the economy&apos;s productive capacity',
      'Short-run aggregate supply is always perfectly elastic at the current price level'
    ],
    ans:0,
    exp:'<strong>Hysteresis</strong> is the idea that demand-side shocks can have permanent supply-side effects. A deep, prolonged recession can erode LRAS: long-term unemployed workers lose skills and motivation (<em>human capital depreciation</em>); firms delay or cancel investment, so the capital stock shrinks; and start-ups that would have been founded never materialise. When recovery comes, the economy&apos;s productive capacity is <em>lower</em> than it would have been without the recession. This challenges the Classical view that recessions are purely temporary: if hysteresis operates, even demand-side policy has long-run supply-side consequences. The concept strengthens the Keynesian case for early, aggressive stimulus to prevent temporary demand shortfalls from becoming permanent capacity losses.'
  }

