    exp:'(0) A high MPM means each round of spending leaks heavily to imports rather than boosting domestic income. (1) A high marginal tax rate removes a large share of each round as tax revenue. (3) Near full employment, extra demand produces inflation rather than real output &mdash; the <em>real</em> multiplier shrinks even if the nominal multiplier is unchanged. (4) A high MPS means households save rather than re-spend. Options 2 and 5 would <em>increase</em> the multiplier: higher confidence raises MPC (less saving), and spare capacity means demand translates into real output rather than price increases.'
