    exp:'(0) <strong>Primary product dependency</strong> exposes countries to price volatility and discourages diversification (Dutch Disease). (1) <strong>Weak institutions</strong> deter investment, reduce aid effectiveness, and create rent-seeking rather than productive activity. (2) <strong>Inadequate infrastructure</strong> raises transport and production costs, isolating rural areas from markets. (3) The <strong>savings gap</strong> (Harrod-Domar) means domestic resources cannot fund the investment needed for sustained growth. Options 4 and 5 are features that <em>promote</em> development: a diversified export base reduces commodity dependence, and strong property rights encourage investment. The barriers are interconnected &mdash; commodity dependence funds patronage that weakens institutions, while poor infrastructure raises costs that deter the diversification needed to escape commodity dependence.'
